<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Freight Transport Association</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from the Freight Transport Association (SRN 052)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">FTA is one of the UK’s largest trade associations and represents over 14,000 companies relying on or providing the transport of freight both domestically and internationally, to or from the UK.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> Our members include hauliers, freight forwarders, rail and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">air freight operators, through to customers – producers, manufacturers, wholesalers and retailers.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> They cover all modes of transport – road, rail, air and sea.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> FTA members operate over 200,000 commercial goods vehicles on the roads in the UK; which is ap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">proximately half of the UK fleet of goods vehicles. FTA members also consign around 90 per cent of goods moved by rail and around 70 per cent of goods moved by air and sea.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Efficient and effective infrastructure networks are essential to the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> functioning of the UK economy. The ongoing difficult economic conditions have, to some extent, masked the impact of congestion and unreliability. Congestion is a drag on businesses and the UK’s international competitiveness is vital to securing economic g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rowth and job creation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Businesses are becoming increasingly concerned about the ability of infrastructure networks to cope with the changing demands that will be placed upon them once there is a return to growth. Government statements on the need to inve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">st in infrastructure have provided some welcome reassurance. But if businesses are to have the confidence necessary to invest, develop and innovate to support their customers, Government will need </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to demonstrate that it has a clear strategy, backed up with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> solid financial support (whatever its source), to ensure that the UK’s infrastructure will be able to meet business needs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Logistics and the Strategic Road Network</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The logistics industry relies on the Strategic Road Network (SRN) for the majority of goo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s deliveries within</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> supply chains. Almost all freight travels on roads for at least part of its journey; and the Strategic Road Network is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> generally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fastes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t, most reliable and most efficient route between many places where goods are made, repackaged, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sold and exported.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The network needs to be well connected and reliable. If that reliability is threatened by congestion the industry look</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to Government funding steams to improve the road system. The network needs to have capacity to deal with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">foreseeable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and unforeseeable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> incidents which it currently lacks in many parts of the road system.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">FTA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can see that the policies set out in “Action for Roads” begin to address the some of industry’s concerns which have been created by a stop start system </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of investment funding mainly due to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">shifting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">priorities when government change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or the economy becomes worse. We believe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> therefore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that there is a need for certainty of funding goi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng forward. It will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> save government money in the long run by ensuring th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at investment is not wasted on dropped schemes but also provide some surety in the framework of logistics planning which looks to use the network for the efficient movement of goods and services. Action for Roads recognises that the SRN is likely to face g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reater pressure from additional t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">raffic. In places routes are well</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> over the capacity that it was designed to accommodate and it will need to be enhance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d going forward. FTA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will look to see that the promised funding to improve the current shortfalls in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">network are delivered but additionally keep the network under review to establish what future funding needs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, from whichever source,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are required to ensure that the freight industry maintains it high level of efficiency. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Of course the SRN </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">represents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> only</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> part of the whole network required for the logistics industry and local a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uthority roads are often cited</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as being in more nee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d of investment. FTA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> notes that Action for Roads </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">looks to local highways authorities to benefit from best practice shared on roads</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to improve maintenance and we believe that they should be held to account for the standard of infrastructure they provide. Badly maintained roads incur cost for the freight industry and while some of the cost for vehicle damage can be recovered very often</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it is absorbed into general maintenance cost. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Additionally the cost of congestion, which can be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">staggeringly high for larger fleets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, is mostly absorbed into product cost and passed on in increasing transportation co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sts to clients and thereby consumers; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">thus stoking inflation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Local highway aut</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">horities should include</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the provision of efficient freight networks as their priorities in the same way as they prioritise passenger transport. Freight movements will be at t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he core of economic efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have the same level of concern at the local level as other modes of transport.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Road Planning compared to other transport modes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although the recession has led to some easing of pressure on the road network, our transport infrastructure is still not in a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fit state to cope with an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> upturn in traffic and trade. In</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2012, the World Economi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Forum ranked the UK 24</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for the overall quality of its infrastructure, behind 13 European countries and other advanced economies. European competitors such as France came fifth, and Germany came ninth.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> When surveyed, the opinion of British businesses endorsed this finding – almo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">st two-thirds (61 per cent) of companies rated the UK’s transport infrastructure as below average by international standards with just 14 per cent deeming it to be above average.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">FTA believes that the UK needs stable, long-term investment in infrastructure programmes to promote growth and support manufacturing and regional economies. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, currently</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">start </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for roads </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prevails which seems </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to FTA to be fundamentally </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">different from rail funding where there is a 5 year committed settlement for the network </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">allows Network Rail the opportunity to plan with more certainty. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">much-vaunted but rarely realised </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">investment programmes for roads that we have seen over rece</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nt years have lead to a significant waste of money when schemes have to be stopped and in some cases restarted again. The strategy proposed in Action for Roads appears to look to get better value for the investment available for the network and we would ho</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pe to see more confidence in the road programme.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network and the impact of new technology?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The reliability and efficiency of travel on the network can be influenced by the use of modern communica</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tions and technology. Freight fleet operators are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> constantly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> looking at opportunities to improve the efficiency of their fleet</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s by better control and management</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. That control will be improved with the provision of data sources on road information. A better</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> understanding of diversion routes when the main network comes under stress</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> passed to operators digitally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> would help with operational planning and management as could faster communication of incidents to let operators make tactical decisions on how to di</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vert or hold back their fleets. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dustry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is making increasing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> use</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> severe weather warnings to make decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on deliveries. The communication of these types of incidents in the future could become almost seamless with data pushed direct</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> into operat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ional control systems for all types of incidents not just those for severe weather events. If vehicles can avoid joining the back</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of queues or stay out of areas where they will be incurring costs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">simply while </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">standing still</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, then</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> there will be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">significant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cost reductions to logistics and customers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Finding new sources of funding</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Businesses see the quality and reliability of transport networks as more important to their investment intentions than any other type of infrastructure, and UK logistics is curr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ently hugely dependent o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">publicly funded transport networks. Following the General Election in 2010, the Highway’s Agency’s capital spending budget was slashed by 35 percent, as part of the wide-spread funding cuts that were made to address the deficit. S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ince the cuts were made, Government made a commitment to fund a number of projects, but there remains some concern over the affordability of all the schemes that are needed to make the SRN fit for enabling growth.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Finding alternative sources of funding th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">erefore has become a necessity, and the Government’s recent proposals for the A14 demonstrate its determination to move forward with this agenda. FTA is not o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pposed to using private finance;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> nor indeed to the principle of some form of tolling. But</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> there ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e a great many potential pitfalls. In view of this, FTA believes there are a number of conditions which would need to be met before such a policy could secure support, not least of which is that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the pricing structure needs to be realistic for FTA members a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd designed in a way which does not artificially deter heavy goods vehicles nor further hamper UK operators’ ability to compete with foreign competitors.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Other conditions include: visibility of charging elements; compensatory reduction in fuel duty; availa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bility of alternative non-tolled route; minimum service levels; lower rates for less polluting and less road-wearing vehicles; harmonised national basis for charge and payment technology; toll revenue to be invested in the routes to which they apply; decla</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ration of new building programme.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Highways Agency reformed to make it “the world’s leading highway operator” </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Association believes that the move to change the Highways Agency from an executive agency of central government to create a publicly own</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> strategic highways company has merit in a number of areas. We have already discussed in this paper the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> need for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> surety of funding over a reasonably long period moving away from the year by year, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and sometimes lesser periods</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, of funding approval. We al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">so suspect that moving from a Civil Service structure to allow the Agency to recruit in and bring in the best of expertise will also help the Agency develop internally to meet its aims of becoming a truly world class roads service provider.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However we hav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">significant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">concern</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">about ensuring</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> accountability. We have for some time tried to work out how the current Agency can be better accountable to the road user. Its current closely align</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> place next to the Department for Transport can all to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> easily miss </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">out the road user and can lead to the Agency being held accountable to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the wrong groups</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It will be important going forward that a body is created by government that will be able to hold the new company to account on the network reliability and standards o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f service. That body must have powers that both the new company and government will recognise in order that recommendations for improvement in reliability, efficiency and environmental standards are met which work toward </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an improved service for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the road us</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – whether they are freight operators or individual private motorists.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> 2013</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:right;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Better connected, better business, CBI/KPMG infrastructure survey</span></p></body></html>